Problem Statement¶

Context¶

The ability to process visual information using machine learning algorithms can be very useful as demonstrated in various applications. The Street View House Numbers (SVHN) dataset is one of the most popular ones. It has been used in neural networks created by Google to read house numbers and match them to their geolocations.

Objective¶

To build a model that can identify house numbers in an image.

Data Dictionary¶

  • Number of classes: 10
  • Training data: 42000 images
  • Testing data: 18000 images

def plot(history, name):
    """
    Function to plot loss/accuracy

    history: an object which stores the metrics and losses.
    name: can be one of Loss or Accuracy
    """
    fig, ax = plt.subplots() #Creating a subplot with figure and axes.
    plt.plot(history.history[name]) #Plotting the train accuracy or train loss
    plt.plot(history.history['val_'+name]) #Plotting the validation accuracy or validation loss

    plt.title('Model ' + name.capitalize()) #Defining the title of the plot.
    plt.ylabel(name.capitalize()) #Capitalizing the first letter.
    plt.xlabel('Epoch') #Defining the label for the x-axis.
    fig.legend(['Train', 'Validation'], loc="outside right upper") #Defining the legend, loc controls the position of the legend.

Let's create a function for plotting the confusion matrix

In [17]:
def make_confusion_matrix(cf,
                          group_names=None,
                          categories='auto',
                          count=True,
                          percent=True,
                          cbar=True,
                          xyticks=True,
                          xyplotlabels=True,
                          sum_stats=True,
                          figsize=(20, 15),
                          cmap='Blues',
                          title=None):
    '''
    This function will make a pretty plot of an sklearn Confusion Matrix cm using a Seaborn heatmap visualization.
    Arguments
    '''


    # CODE TO GENERATE TEXT INSIDE EACH SQUARE
    blanks = ['' for i in range(cf.size)]

    if group_names and len(group_names)==cf.size:
        group_labels = ["{}\n".format(value) for value in group_names]
    else:
        group_labels = blanks

    if count:
        group_counts = ["{0:0.0f}\n".format(value) for value in cf.flatten()]
    else:
        group_counts = blanks

    if percent:
        group_percentages = ["{0:.2%}".format(value) for value in cf.flatten()/np.sum(cf)]
    else:
        group_percentages = blanks

    box_labels = [f"{v1}{v2}{v3}".strip() for v1, v2, v3 in zip(group_labels,group_counts,group_percentages)]
    box_labels = np.asarray(box_labels).reshape(cf.shape[0],cf.shape[1])


    # CODE TO GENERATE SUMMARY STATISTICS & TEXT FOR SUMMARY STATS
    if sum_stats:
        #Accuracy is sum of diagonal divided by total observations
        accuracy  = np.trace(cf) / float(np.sum(cf))

        #if it is a binary confusion matrix, show some more stats
        if len(cf)==2:
            #Metrics for Binary Confusion Matrices
            precision = cf[1,1] / sum(cf[:,1])
            recall    = cf[1,1] / sum(cf[1,:])
            f1_score  = 2*precision*recall / (precision + recall)
            stats_text = "\n\nAccuracy={:0.3f}\nPrecision={:0.3f}\nRecall={:0.3f}\nF1 Score={:0.3f}".format(
                accuracy,precision,recall,f1_score)
        else:
            stats_text = "\n\nAccuracy={:0.3f}".format(accuracy)
    else:
        stats_text = ""


    # SET FIGURE PARAMETERS ACCORDING TO OTHER ARGUMENTS
    if figsize==None:
        #Get default figure size if not set
        figsize = plt.rcParams.get('figure.figsize')

    if xyticks==False:
        #Do not show categories if xyticks is False
        categories=False


    # MAKE THE HEATMAP VISUALIZATION
    plt.figure(figsize=figsize)
    sns.heatmap(cf,annot=box_labels,fmt="",cmap=cmap,cbar=cbar,xticklabels=categories,yticklabels=categories)

    if xyplotlabels:
        plt.ylabel('True label')
        plt.xlabel('Predicted label' + stats_text)
    else:
        plt.xlabel(stats_text)

    if title:
        plt.title(title)

# Function to clear backend and fixing seed for random number generators so that we can ensure we receive the same output everytime
def BackendClearSession():
    backend.clear_session()
    np.random.seed(42)
    random.seed(42)
    tf.random.set_seed(42)

# Function to save recall score of train and test data of each model by name
def save_recall_score(model, model_name):
  # Predicting train data results
  y_train_pred = model.predict(X_train)

  # Predicting test data results
  y_test_pred = model.predict(X_test)

  # Convert predicted probabilities to class labels using argmax
  y_train_pred_argmax = np.argmax(y_train_pred, axis=1)
  y_test_pred_argmax = np.argmax(y_test_pred, axis=1)

  # Convert the one-hot encoded true labels to single class labels
  y_train_true_argmax = np.argmax(y_train_en, axis=1)
  y_test_true_argmax = np.argmax(y_test_en, axis=1)

  # Calculate recall score using the predicted class labels and the converted true labels
  train_metric_df.loc[model_name] = recall_score(y_train_true_argmax, y_train_pred_argmax, average='weighted')
  test_metric_df.loc[model_name] = recall_score(y_test_true_argmax, y_test_pred_argmax, average='weighted')
In [20]:
# defining a function to compute different metrics to check performance of model built using statsmodels
def model_performance_classification(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """
    # Predicting target data with dependant variables
    y_pred = model.predict(predictors)

    # Convert predicted probabilities to class labels using argmax
    y_pred_argmax = np.argmax(y_pred, axis=1)

    # Convert the one-hot encoded true labels to single class labels
    target_argmax = np.argmax(target, axis=1)

    # Use the single class labels for calculating metrics
    acc = accuracy_score(target_argmax, y_pred_argmax)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target_argmax, y_pred_argmax, average='weighted')  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target_argmax, y_pred_argmax, average='weighted')  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target_argmax, y_pred_argmax, average='weighted')  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {"Accuracy": acc, "Recall": recall, "Precision": precision, "F1 Score": f1,},
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf

## Initializing Neural Network
model_2 = Sequential()

## Add input layer with 64 neurons and relu as activation function
model_2.add(Dense(64, activation='relu', input_dim = X_train.shape[1]))

## First hidden layer with 32 neurons with relu as activation functions
model_2.add(Dense(32, activation='relu'))

## Add the output layer with softmax as activation function with 10 neurons (We are predicting 10 classes)
model_2.add(Dense(10, activation = 'softmax'))

# Adam Optimizer
optimizer = tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(0.001)

## Compile Model with binary cross entropy as loss function and accuracy as metrics
model_2.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy', optimizer=optimizer, metrics=['accuracy', 'recall'])

#Initializing the neural network
model_5 = Sequential()

## Add input layer with 32 neurons and relu as activation function
model_5.add(Dense(32, activation='relu', kernel_initializer="he_normal", input_dim = X_train.shape[1]))

## Add dropout with dropout_rate= 0.4
model_5.add(Dropout(0.4))
## Add Hiden layer with 16 neurons and relu as activation function
model_5.add(Dense(16, activation='relu', kernel_initializer="he_normal"))

## Add dropout with dropout_rate= 0.2
model_5.add(Dropout(0.2))
## Add Hiden layer with 8 neurons and relu as activation function
model_5.add(Dense(8, activation='relu', kernel_initializer="he_normal"))

## Add Output layer with sigmoid as activation function with 10 neurons (Predicting 10 classes)
model_5.add(Dense(10, activation = 'sigmoid' , kernel_initializer="he_normal"))

Actionable Insights and Business Recommendations¶

  • The Street View House Numbers final model from this exercise can be deployed to identify with a reasonable degree of accuracy to read house numbers in images and match them to their geolocations, and this process seems to be easier and more time-efficient than other methods.

  • One can employ techniques like oversampling minority classes, using appropriate evaluation metrics (e.g., F1-score), or employing ensemble methods like SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Over-sampling Technique) to address class imbalance. Ensuring a balanced dataset is crucial for model training to avoid biased predictions.

🔍Insights from Analysis¶

Digit Frequency Imbalance

The dataset shows a non-uniform distribution of digits. For example, digits like 1, 2, and 0 appear more frequently than 8 or 9.

This imbalance can affect the performance of a digit recognition model, leading to biased predictions toward more frequent digits.

Location-aware Digit Patterns

In real-world scenarios, certain digit patterns correlate with geographic regions (e.g., U.S. ZIP codes or street numbering systems).

Although SVHN doesn't provide GPS labels, combining its outputs with geo-tagged data could support geo-contextual modeling.

📈 Business Recommendations¶

Enhance Geolocation Accuracy for Mapping Services

Integrate a model trained on SVHN into Google Maps or Waze to improve address resolution, especially in areas with poor address labeling or low-resolution imagery.

Automate Property Cataloging for Real Estate Platforms

Use digit detection to auto-tag properties with street numbers, accelerating the cataloging of real estate listings and reducing manual effort in verifying property addresses.

Improve Delivery Logistics for E-commerce and Courier Services

Partner with delivery companies (e.g., FedEx, Amazon) to provide digit recognition APIs that identify house numbers from delivery driver's street-view footage in real time.

Aid in Urban Planning and Infrastructure Audits

Governments and urban planners can use models trained on SVHN for address verification, helping in census activities, infrastructure monitoring, or property tax audits.

Enable Smart City Navigation Features

Integrate number-recognition models into autonomous vehicles or smart glasses to help them locate buildings more precisely using street-facing cameras.

Support Accessibility Innovations

Digit recognition can be embedded into assistive devices for the visually impaired, enabling them to recognize and be alerted to house numbers as they navigate neighborhoods.

Extend the Dataset with Contextual Metadata

Business opportunity exists in extending SVHN-like datasets with contextual information (e.g., GPS, time of day, weather), opening the door for context-aware AI systems.

✅ Summary

The SVHN dataset provides an excellent real-world testbed for digit recognition under diverse and challenging conditions. Businesses across mapping, logistics, real estate, urban planning, and accessibility tech can leverage trained models to automate and enhance geolocation services. Improving dataset annotations (e.g., house number sequences or GPS tagging) would further unlock valuable commercial applications.
